\cf2 /* Extending your SCClassLibrary.  SuperCollider is a user-extensible system, and most users eventually write their own Classes to use in different contexts.  Sharing these is one of the advantages of working in a free software environment.  The SC-swiki site is a repository for shared classes, where users can post their own and download other people's contributions.  Here is the url:  http://swiki.hfbk-hamburg.de:8888/MusicTechnology/6\
\
Former CCM student Michael Cox created a number of Classes that provide convenient GUI controls that we'll start using this week. His AutoGui class automatically creates a set of SCSliders and SCNumberBoxes, along with a built-in Preset class to save and recall their settings.  To use them, you first need to download them from the link on the syllabus.  After downloading and unpacking them, drag the "DeadNet_Classes" folder into your SuperCollider subfolder called "SCClassLibrary".  \ul You must also remove the "Preset" folder from the same SCClassLibrary folder, because it has conflicting code.\ulnone   (This contains another library written at Wesleyan that we may be using this later in the course, so save it somewhere on your disk -- you could just move it up one directory level, within SC# but outside the SCClassLibrary folder.  Then either startup SC3, or if it's already started, type "command-K", to recompile your class library.\
\
We will use AutoGui to explore combinations of noise generators and various filters available in SC3.\
\
	1) noise classes:  WhiteNoise, PinkNoise, BrownNoise, ClipNoise, Crackle\
		WhiteNoise	= equal power noise at all frequencies\
		PinkNoise = equal power noise at exponential freq\
		 						distribution (equal in each octave)\
		BrownNoise = noise with power that drops 6 db per next octave\
		ClipNoise = maximum energy noise, all samples are either\
						+1 or -1\
		Crackle = noise based on a chaotic function generator\
	\
	2) filter classes: \
		LPF, 			// low-pass filter\
		HPF, 			// high-pass filter\
		BPF,			// bandpass filter \
		Resonz, 	// resonant bandpass filter\
		RLPF, 		// resonant lowpass filter\
		RHPF, 		// resonant highpass filter\
		Ringz, 		// same as Resonz, but resonance in "ring-time"\
	\
	*/\cf0 \
\
( \cf2 // begin by compiling this SynthDef\cf0 \
\pard\tx560\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\ql\qnatural
\cf3 SynthDef\cf0 (\cf4 "noise-filters"\cf0 ,\{ \cf3 arg\cf0  freq=200, white=0, pink=0, 	brown=0, clip=0, crkl=0, crPrm=1.95, lpf=0, 	hpf=0, bpf=0, rlpf=0, rhpf=0, resz=0,  rq=0.1, 	ringz=0, dcy=1, vol=0.5;\
	\cf3 var\cf0  noiseMix;\
	noiseMix = \cf3 Mix\cf0 .new([ \
		\cf3 WhiteNoise\cf0 .ar(white),	\cf2 // equal power all frequencies\cf0 \
		\cf3 PinkNoise\cf0 .ar(pink),	\cf2 // spectrum decays 3dB per octave\cf0 \
		\cf3 BrownNoise\cf0 .ar(brown), \cf2 // spectrum decays 3dB per octave\cf0 \
		\cf3 ClipNoise\cf0 .ar(clip),  \cf2 // all values are -1 or =1, max energy\cf0 \
		\cf3 Crackle\cf0 .ar(crPrm,crkl) \cf2 // chaotic function, crParm crackles!\cf0 \
	]);\
	\cf3 Out\cf0 .ar(0,\cf3 Mix\cf0 .new([\
		\cf2 // these filters have no gain\cf0 \
		\cf3 LPF\cf0 .ar(noiseMix,freq, lpf),\
		\cf3 HPF\cf0 .ar(noiseMix,freq, hpf),\
		\cf3 BPF\cf0 .ar(noiseMix,freq, rq, bpf),\
		\cf2 // these filters have gain in the passband -- rq is the bandwidth ratio (reciprocal of filter's Q), rq = bandwidth/centerFreq \cf0 \
		\cf3 RLPF\cf0 .ar(noiseMix,freq,rq,rlpf),\
		\cf3 RHPF\cf0 .ar(noiseMix,freq,rq,rhpf),\
		\cf3 Resonz\cf0 .ar(noiseMix,freq, rq, resz),\
		\cf3 Ringz\cf0 .ar(noiseMix,freq, dcy, ringz)\
	])*vol); \cf5 //* = multiplied by the volume arg\cf0 \
\}).store;	\cf2 // we 'store' the SynthDef here, instead of just loading it.  This writes the definition as a file called 'name.scsyndef' into the default directory, from which it will automatically load (on this machine) the next time you recompile SC3.  This means you don't have to load it anymore before using it.  It also stores stores a SynthDesc (synth-description)  in SynthDescLib, which contains its name, its control(argument) names, and default values, which is how AutoGui will know to create GUI items for it.\cf0 \
)\
