\cf2 /* \
You already know about ControlSpec, the Class that automatically maps a slider's output from its normal 0->1 range to any range you like, using many different possible warp (or curves) -- for example:\
\
//	ControlSpec.new( minval, maxval, warp, step, default,units);\
a = ControlSpec(40,4000,\\exp,0,1) 		// 'new' is a default method\
a.map(0.5)\
\
To use you AutoGui you need to create ControlSpecs for each of the named arguments that you want to control with a slider.\
\
*/\cf0 \
(	\cf2 // create these named ControlSpecs, and add them to the library in 'Spec', the superclass. Make a list, then define them as symbols. \cf0 \
\pard\tx560\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\ql\qnatural
\cf3 Spec\cf0 .specs.addAll([\
	\cf6 \\white\cf0 ->\cf3 ControlSpec\cf0 .specs.at(\cf6 \\amp\cf0 ), \
	\cf6 \\pink\cf0 ->\cf3 ControlSpec\cf0 .specs.at(\cf6 \\amp\cf0 ), \
	\cf6 \\brown\cf0 ->\cf3 ControlSpec\cf0 .specs.at(\cf6 \\amp\cf0 ), \
	\cf6 \\clip\cf0 ->\cf3 ControlSpec\cf0 .specs.at(\cf6 \\amp\cf0 ), \
	\cf6 \\crPrm\cf0 ->\cf3 ControlSpec\cf0 (1.0,2.01,\cf6 \\linear\cf0 ),\
	\cf6 \\crkl\cf0 ->\cf3 ControlSpec\cf0 .specs.at(\cf6 \\amp\cf0 ), \
	\cf6 \\lpf\cf0 ->\cf3 ControlSpec\cf0 .specs.at(\cf6 \\amp\cf0 ),\
	\cf6 \\hpf\cf0 ->\cf3 ControlSpec\cf0 .specs.at(\cf6 \\amp\cf0 ),\
	\cf6 \\bpf\cf0 ->\cf3 ControlSpec\cf0 .specs.at(\cf6 \\amp\cf0 ),\
	\cf6 \\rlpf\cf0 ->\cf3 ControlSpec\cf0 .specs.at(\cf6 \\amp\cf0 ),\
	\cf6 \\rhpf\cf0 ->\cf3 ControlSpec\cf0 .specs.at(\cf6 \\amp\cf0 ),\
	\cf6 \\resz\cf0 ->\cf3 ControlSpec\cf0 .specs.at(\cf6 \\amp\cf0 ),\
	\cf6 \\rq\cf0 ->\cf3 ControlSpec\cf0 (0.001,4,\cf6 \\exponential\cf0 ),\
	\cf6 \\ringz\cf0 ->\cf3 ControlSpec\cf0 .specs.at(\cf6 \\amp\cf0 ),\
	\cf6 \\dcy\cf0 ->\cf3 ControlSpec\cf0 (0.01,2),\
	\cf6 \\vol\cf0 ->\cf3 ControlSpec\cf0 .specs.at(\cf6 \\amp\cf0 )]\
);\
)\
(	\cf2 // now play the Synth and control it with your new GUI\cf0 \
\cf3 AutoGui\cf0 (\cf3 Synth\cf0 (\cf4 "noise-filters"\cf0 ));\
