\
\cf0 \
\pard\tx560\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\ql\qnatural
\cf2 // The next example shows how you can change Klank's specifications from outside the running Synth -- we will also generate these specs randomly, so the result is about the same, but the means is importantly different!  It allows you to write your own sequences, or send values interactively from SCLang to any running Synth.  It also demonstrates the usage of Server-Commands, which underlie all of the messaging from the language to the Server that we have been using.  Much of the power of the SC environment comes from the ability to have very low-level access to controlling the Server's processes, which are accessed using Server-Commands.\cf0 \
(\
\pard\tx560\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\ql\qnatural
\cf3 SynthDef\cf0 (\cf4 "bell"\cf0 ,\{ \cf3 arg\cf0  freq=440,  vol=0.5;\
	\cf3 var\cf0  harm, amp, ring;\
	harm = \cf3 Control\cf0 .names([\cf6 \\harm\cf0 ]).ir(\cf3 Array\cf0 .series(4,1,1));\
	amp = \cf3 Control\cf0 .names([\cf6 \\amp\cf0 ]).ir(\cf3 Array\cf0 .fill(4,0.5));\
	ring = \cf3 Control\cf0 .names([\cf6 \\ring\cf0 ]).ir(\cf3 Array\cf0 .fill(4,1));\
	\cf2 // a Control is the way to bring information into a running Synth (arguments to SynthDefs are implemented via Controls).  We use it here because this is the only way to send Arrays, not just single values, to a running Synth (Arrays cannot be arguments of a Synth).  The 'ir' method applied to Control means 'initialization rate' and initializes the Control's Array\cf0 \
	\cf3 Out\cf0 .ar(0,\cf3 Klank\cf0 .ar(`[harm,amp,ring],\
	\cf2 // the input is an array of two versions of the "striker"\cf0 \
		\{\cf3 Decay\cf0 .ar(\cf3 Impulse\cf0 .ar(0.05),0.03,\cf3 ClipNoise\cf0 .ar(0.01))\}.dup, \
		freq)	 \cf2 // the freqScale arg sets a "fundamental" frequency\cf0 \
		*\cf3 EnvGen\cf0 .ar(\cf3 Env\cf0 .perc(0.1,0.5,vol), doneAction: 2)	\cf2 // multiply the Klank by an EnvGen, that kills the Synth\cf0 \
	\cf2 // when it ends\cf0 \
	)\
\}).store;\
)\
\pard\tx560\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\ql\qnatural
\cf2 /* with Klank, the specification array cannot be changed after\
a Synth has started, and to change the array between notes and after compilation we have to send new arrays to its Synth on the server. In order to do this,we use a lower-level message system, "s.sendBundle", which here sends a number of messages in an OSC package to the server, so that when the server starts a new note obeying the command "s_new" (which is always sent whenever we create a Synth), it does so with new Controls, which have been set using "/n_setn" -- see the help-file Server-Command-Reference for a complete list of these type of commands.  they underlie all of the higher level commands we have been using, such as Synth.new();\
*/\cf0 \
(\
\pard\tx560\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\ql\qnatural
\cf3 Routine\cf0 (\{ \
	\cf3 var\cf0  ctr=2000;	\cf2 // this will be the starting NodeID \cf0 \
	loop(\{ \
		ctr = (ctr+1);	\cf2 // we create a series of Synths\cf0 \
						\cf2 // with increasing NodeIDs\cf0 \
		s.sendBundle(\cf3 nil\cf0 ,\
	\cf2 // the next message is the one that starts a Synth\cf0 \
			[\cf4 "/s_new"\cf0 , \cf4 "bell"\cf0 , ctr, 1, 0, \cf6 \\freq\cf0 , rrand(200,800)],\
	\cf2 /* the next message sets a series of Controls --\
	 it says, set a number of Controls of the 'ctr' Synth\
	 starting at the one named "harm", changing a total\
	 of 4, which are the next 4 numbers, as created by 	Array.rand. \
	 the operator ++ concatenates (joins) two Arrays\
	*/\cf0 \
			[\cf4 "/n_setn"\cf0 ,ctr,\cf4 "harm"\cf0 , 4]++ \cf3 Array\cf0 .rand(4,1,17),\
			[\cf4 "/n_setn"\cf0 , ctr, \cf4 "ring"\cf0 , 4] ++\
									 \cf3 Array\cf0 .fill(4,rrand(0.1,1.0)),\
			[\cf4 "/n_setn"\cf0 , ctr, \cf4 "amp"\cf0 , 4] ++ \cf3 Array\cf0 .fill(4,0.2)\
		);		\cf2 // this is the end of the bundled message\cf0 \
		0.1.wait\
	\});\
\}).play;\
)\
\
\pard\tx560\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\ql\qnatural
\cf2 /* let's use the same technique to create a changing additive Synth -- FSinOsc is a sine oscillator that runs much faster than SinOsc does.   */\cf0 \
